Data analysis

sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is moderate (conditional R2 = 0.20) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.10. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 20.58 (S.E. = 1.05, p < .001, 95% CI [18.53, 22.64]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.03, S.E. = 0.02, p = 0.106, 95% CI [-0.08, 7.31e-03]; Std. beta = -0.24, 95% CI [-0.53, 0.05])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.63, S.E. = 0.39, p = 0.105, 95% CI [-0.13, 1.40]; Std. beta = 0.27, 95% CI [-0.06, 0.59])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.71, S.E. = 0.71, p = 0.316, 95% CI [-0.68, 2.09]; Std. beta = 0.32, 95% CI [-0.31, 0.95])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
